On May 4, 2007, at 8:26 AM, Rachel Morton wrote:

> http://www.sacbee.com/111/story/167168.html
>
> Sacramento Bee
> Prison package hailed
>
> At signing ceremony, rehabilitation policy seen as a major shift.
>
> By Andy Furillo - Bee Capitol Bureau
>
> Published 12:00 am PDT Friday, May 4, 2007
> Story appeared in MAIN NEWS section, Page A1
>
> Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger and legislative leaders promised a new =20
> era for California corrections Thursday, one where the prison =20
> system's operative philosophy of the past two decades -- =20
> warehousing inmates -- will give way to offering them a chance at =20
> rehabilitation.
>
> At a signing ceremony on the Capitol's east steps, Schwarzenegger =20
> hailed the prison package contained in Assembly Bill 900 as =20
> representing a "monumental shift in how we manage prisons."
>
> In the short term, the state is hoping that the $7.9 billion plan =20
> that adds space for 53,000 prison and jail beds will dissuade =20
> federal judges from imposing population caps that could lead to =20
> early releases of inmates from California's jampacked prisons. In =20
> the long run, the hope is that it will keep prisoners from =20
> reoffending.
>
> "Our job is far from done," Schwarzenegger said. "We have made the =20
> commitment to provide the infrastructure we need to relieve =20
> overcrowding. And now we must follow through on the rehabilitation =20
> programs that we need to make sure that inmates who get released =20
> can lead productive, law-abiding lives so that our communities will =20=

> stay safe."
>
> At the end of the 2005-06 budget year, only 10,572 of the 171,900 =20
> inmates incarcerated at that time were enrolled in academic =20
> education programs and only 7,953 were in vocational programs. =20
> About 8,500 more prisoners were in drug treatment programs.
>
> Under the bill Schwarzenegger signed Thursday, all of the proposed =20
> 40,000 new beds expected to come on line in the California =20
> Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation will be linked to =20
> mental health, vocational, education and drug-treatment programs.
>
> Joan Petersilia, head of the University of California, Irvine, =20
> Center for Evidence-Based Corrections, said that AB 900 represents =20
> a "historic turning point for California," where 172,344 inmates =20
> are being housed in spaces designed for about half that many.
>
> "We're going to build the space so people can learn jobs," =20
> Petersilia, who has worked as a consultant to the state prison =20
> system for the past three years, said at the signing ceremony. =20
> "We're going to increase their literacy rate. And we can provide =20
> good, solid substance abuse treatment programs."
>
> Petersilia added, however, that "we should not underestimate the =20
> difficulty of implementing this package." In an interview =20
> afterward, she cited staff vacancies throughout the prison system, =20
> its culture of punishment-over-rehabilitation and skepticism in the =20=

> public mind as critical barriers the state has to overcome to make =20
> the program work.
>
> The plan calls for building space for 16,000 beds at existing =20
> prisons, 16,000 more at 30 or so "re-entry" centers to be located =20
> around the state and 8,000 additional beds at new correctional =20
> hospitals. The other 13,000 beds are slated for county jails, which =20=

> are now releasing 18,000 inmates a month due to overcrowding.
>
> Sacramento County is one of about 25 communities around the state =20
> that have expressed an interest in housing a re-entry facility. Its =20=

> district attorney, Jan Scully, said in an interview she believes =20
> the public will support the idea.
>
> "I think that citizens are always concerned about whether or not =20
> it's in their own neighborhood, so I think there is going to have =20
> to be a lot of discussion, and the community is going to have to =20
> feel that it's in their best interest to have such a facility close =20=

> by," Scully said. "I think it's going to be important for the Board =20=

> of Supervisors to hold public hearings and those kinds of things. =20
> There's going to be a lot of homework to do first."
>
> Scully described herself as "a big proponent of re-entry =20
> opportunities" and said she would help to get one located in =20
> Sacramento.
>
> The bill breaks the construction program into two phases. The =20
> second can only proceed if the state proves it has met the =20
> rehabilitation requirements in the first, 32,000-bed phase of the =20
> program.
>
> The 16,000 new beds would go into 10 existing prisons around the =20
> state to replace emergency housing in which triple-bunked inmates =20
> are sleeping in gyms, dayrooms and classrooms.
>
> AB 900 also includes legislative approval of Schwarzenegger's =20
> emergency plan to ship 8,000 inmates -- against their will, if =20
> necessary -- to out-of-state prisons. The transfer plan has been =20
> held up by lawsuits filed by the California Correctional Peace =20
> Officers Association and Service Employees International Union =20
> Local 1000.
>
> Another provision in the bill will convert 4,000 existing prison =20
> beds into drug-treatment slots for inmates.
>
> The bill contains an urgency provision that allows corrections =20
> officials to begin construction immediately. Schwarzenegger said =20
> Thursday he expects the construction to be completed within 18 months.
>
> Opponents of the bill such as state Sen. Gloria Romero, D-Los =20
> Angeles, said it represents just another prison construction plan =20
> for the state and that the administration missed a chance to =20
> incorporate a major sentencing overhaul and parole changes into the =20=

> package, items that opponents said might reduce the need for new =20
> incarceration spaces in the future.
>
> Schwarzenegger pledged Thursday that he is open to discussing =20
> sentencing and parole changes later in the legislative session. He =20
> also said he will continue to push a plan to relocate 4,500 =20
> nonviolent female offenders to community-based facilities to open =20
> up prison space to more dangerous offenders.
>
> Assembly Speaker Fabian N=FA=F1ez, D-Los Angeles, said nobody got =20
> everything they wanted in AB 900. In signing the bill, =20
> Schwarzenegger made "a contract with the people of California" and =20
> "the Legislature is going to be watching" to make sure the prison =20
> agency follows through on the rehabilitation benchmarks, N=FA=F1ez =
said.
>
> "This would have been an easy problem to solve if we were simply =20
> willing to build prison after prison, like houses on a Monopoly =20
> board," N=FA=F1ez said. "But we weren't."
>
> Assembly Republican leader Mike Villines of Clovis said the package =20=

> represents bipartisan cooperation at its finest.
>
> "Republicans and Democrats put their differences aside," he said. =20
> "We put California first."
>
